matplotlib¶

There are several Python visualization tools being matplotlib the most developed 2d/3d general purpose plotting package. The syntax is very similar to matlab.

plot¶

cond=sst>1e30
sst=np.ma.masked_where(cond,sst) # masked regions are not considered

fig,ax=pl.subplots(1,2)
fig.set_size_inches((10,3.5))

h=ax[0].contourf(x,y,sst,np.arange(8,15,1),extend='max')
l=ax[0].contour(x,y,sst,np.arange(12,15,1),colors='k')
cb=pl.colorbar(h,ax=ax[0]);
cb.add_lines(l)

h=ax[1].pcolormesh(x,y,sst,vmin=10,vmax=15,cmap=pl.cm.bone)
l=ax[1].contour(x,y,sst,[13,14],colors='m');
cb=pl.colorbar(h,ax=ax[1]);
cb.add_lines(l)

annotations and text boxes¶

It is very easy to add and manipulate text and labels, including latex code.

In [17]:

            arrowprops=dict(facecolor='pink',ec='green', shrink=0.05),
            )
pl.legend(loc='lower left')
pl.title('TEMP ($^\mathrm{o}$C) $\int_0^\infty \mathrm{e}^{-x}\,\mathrm{d}x$')
ax=pl.gca()

time series¶

Matplotlib can deal with dates as arrays of datetime objects, e.g.:

In [20]:
a=np.load('data/ts/itajai.npz',allow_pickle=True)
t=a['time']
q=a['q']
pl.plot(t,q)
pl.gcf().set_size_inches((9,3))

let's make this look better...

In [21]:
import datetime
date0=datetime.datetime(2013,1,1)
date1=datetime.datetime(2016,1,1)

fig,ax=pl.subplots(1)
fig.set_size_inches((9,3))
ax.plot(t,q)

ax.set_xlim(date0,date1)
ax.set_ylim(0,5000)
ax.xaxis.grid(1)
ax.yaxis.grid(1)

# x ticks and labels:
years=pl.matplotlib.dates.YearLocator()
months=pl.matplotlib.dates.MonthLocator()
yfmt=pl.matplotlib.dates.DateFormatter('%Y')

ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(years)
ax.xaxis.set_tick_params(pad=10)
ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(yfmt)
ax.xaxis.set_minor_locator(months)

d0=datetime.datetime(2014,1,1)
d1=datetime.datetime(2015,1,1)
yl=ax.get_ylim()
ax.fill([d0,d1,d1,d0],[yl[0],yl[0],yl[1],yl[1]],'#fff5d1',zorder=0.9)

import matplotlib.transforms as transforms
# the x coords of this transformation are data, and the
# y coord are axes (0 to 1)
trans = transforms.blended_transform_factory(
    ax.transData, ax.transAxes)

for y in range(2013,2016):
    for m in [3,6,9,12]:
        d=datetime.datetime(y,m-2,16)
        ax.text(d,-0.03,d.strftime('%b').upper(),transform=trans,
                fontsize=7,va='top',ha='center',color='g')
        d=datetime.datetime(y,m,1)
        ax.plot([d,d],ax.get_ylim(),'g--',lw=0.5,alpha=0.7)

transforms¶

In the previous time series example we used a transform to place text using data at x and axes coords at y. Let's play a little with this:

In [22]:
ax=pl.axes()
pl.plot(q[:30])

# put some label at the center of the axes:
pl.text(.5,.5,'CENTRE',ha='center',va='center',transform=ax.transAxes,fontsize=12)
# or at upper left corner:
pl.text(-0.1,1,'a) DISCHARGE (m$^3$ s$^{-1}$)',ha='left',va='bottom',
        transform=ax.transAxes,fontsize=12)

# label at data x,y:
xo=10
yo=300
pl.plot(xo,yo,'r+')
pl.text(xo,yo,'(%d,%d)'%(xo,yo))

# label ax mixed coordinates (end of x axis, y=500):
trans = transforms.blended_transform_factory(
    ax.transAxes, ax.transData)
pl.text(1,500,'LABEL',ha='right',va='center',transform=trans,fontsize=12);
pl.text(1,450,'LABEL',ha='left',va='center',transform=trans,fontsize=12);
pl.text(1.05,450,'LABEL',ha='left',va='top',transform=trans,fontsize=12);

Exercício:¶

usar os dados do Itajaí para criar um box plot
(exercicios/box_plot.py)
1- usar boxplot do matplotlib (pl.boxplot)
2- criar uma funçao para gerar boxplots horizontais!
In [24]:
def ler():
    a=np.load('data/ts/itajai.npz',allow_pickle=True)
    t=a['time']
    q=a['q']
    return t,q

def ver():
    x,y=ler()
    pl.plot(x,y)
    pl.gcf().set_size_inches((9,3))

def ver_box():
    x,y=ler()
    pl.boxplot(y[:100])

ver_box()

def boxploth(x):
    p=np.percentile(x,[5,25,50,75,95])
    fig=pl.figure()
    ax=pl.axes()
    ax.plot([p[0],p[0],p[0],p[-1],p[-1],p[-1]],[1,-1,0,0,1,-1])
    
    ax.fill([p[1],p[1],p[3],p[3],p[1]],[2,-2,-2,2,2],'#cccccc',ec='r',zorder=3)
    ax.plot([p[2],p[2]],[-2,2],'r',zorder=4)
    ax.set_ylim(-5,5)

x,y=ler()
boxploth(y[:1000])
pl.figure()
pl.hist(y[:1000])

Exercício:¶

  • Cria o script exercicios/teste_scatter.py

  • Cria dois vectores u, v aleatórios de distribuiçao normal (np.random.normal) com 1000 elementos.

  • Cria uma figura com 3 subplots

  • Plota um histograma dos dois vectores e faz um scatter plot de u e v.

  • Adicionar mapeamento de cores associado a um terceiro vector (ex.: u^2+v^2)

  • Adiciona colorbar

  • Verifica limite de cores (opçao vmin e vmax do scatter)

  • alterar color map (opçao cmap)
